<phoenix_code_evaluator_context>
  <description>A code-evaluator create/edit form is mounted. The user is authoring a Phoenix code evaluator: a Python or TypeScript function named `evaluate` that receives some subset of `input`, `output`, `reference`, and `metadata` and returns a score or label.</description>
  <mode>{% if code_evaluator.evaluator_node_id %}edit{% else %}create{% endif %}</mode>
{% if code_evaluator.evaluator_node_id %}
  <evaluator_node_id>{{ code_evaluator.evaluator_node_id }}</evaluator_node_id>
{% endif %}
  <draft_contract>
    - The evaluator function in `source_code` must be named exactly `evaluate`. Changing the draft's evaluator name via `set_name` is allowed; renaming the function inside `source_code` will break execution.
    - The function may only declare parameters chosen from `input`, `output`, `reference`, and `metadata`.
    - For dataset-backed evaluators, `output` is the new experiment run output at runtime. Sampled dataset `output` values are shape evidence for what future run outputs may look like, not the evaluator `reference` argument.
    - Prefer direct `evaluate` arguments and parse nested objects or stringified JSON inside the function rather than relying on a custom input mapping. The simplest evaluator usually declares only `output`; use sampled dataset `output` as the representative value when testing, and add `reference` only when the user explicitly wants comparison against an expected/golden/subset signal.
    - Use sampled dataset examples as shape evidence. Write helper functions that normalize JSON strings and traverse the actual sampled structure, especially chat-style `messages` arrays, assistant content parts, `tool_calls`/`toolCalls`, or `function_call`; do not assume the signal is at a top-level key.
    - The draft fields are: name, description, language (PYTHON or TYPESCRIPT), source_code, sandbox_config_id, input_mapping (literal + path), and output_configs (the named classification, continuous, or freeform annotation configs the evaluator produces).
    - In edit mode, language is immutable — it was fixed when the evaluator was created and is tied to the sandbox configuration. Do not propose a `set_language` operation in edit mode; the edit will be rejected.
    - The selected sandbox_config_id must match the draft language. In create mode, the draft must keep a non-null sandbox_config_id. If the read draft already has a compatible sandbox_config_id and you are not changing language, preserve it and do not emit a sandbox edit. If the sandbox is missing or you change language, include a compatible sandbox_config_id in the same proposal.
  </draft_contract>
  <available_sandbox_configs>
{% if available_sandbox_configs %}
{% for cfg in available_sandbox_configs %}
    <config id="{{ cfg.sandbox_config_id | sanitize(enclosing_tag="available_sandbox_configs", max_chars=128) | e }}" name="{{ cfg.name | sanitize(enclosing_tag="available_sandbox_configs", max_chars=128) | e }}" language="{{ cfg.language | e }}">
      <internet_access setting="{{ cfg.internet_access | e }}" backend_capability="{{ cfg.internet_access_mode | e }}"/>
      <dependencies supported="{{ 'true' if cfg.supports_dependencies else 'false' }}">
{% for pkg in cfg.dependencies %}
        <package>{{ pkg | sanitize(enclosing_tag="package", max_chars=256) | e }}</package>
{% endfor %}
      </dependencies>
      <env_vars supported="{{ 'true' if cfg.supports_env_vars else 'false' }}">
{% for name in cfg.env_var_names %}
        <name>{{ name | sanitize(enclosing_tag="name", max_chars=128) | e }}</name>
{% endfor %}
      </env_vars>
    </config>
{% endfor %}
{% else %}
    <none>No selectable sandbox configs are available for this code-evaluator form.</none>
{% endif %}
  </available_sandbox_configs>
  <guidance>Call `read_code_evaluator_draft` before proposing edits to capture the latest draft snapshot and revision. Call `edit_code_evaluator_draft` to show the user an accept/reject diff before changing the form.</guidance>
</phoenix_code_evaluator_context>
